---
import ChapterShell from "../../../components/ChapterShell.astro";
import { localePath } from "../../../lib/i18n";
import Section from "../../../components/Section.astro";
import DiagramFigure from "../../../components/diagrams/DiagramFigure.astro";
import AheBoundaryKeystone from "../../../components/diagrams/AheBoundaryKeystone.astro";
import EvidenceExportFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/EvidenceExportFlow.astro";
import ManifestEvaluateFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/ManifestEvaluateFlow.astro";
import ReadonlyEvidencePlaneFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/ReadonlyEvidencePlaneFlow.astro";
import AuthorityBucketFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/AuthorityBucketFlow.astro";
import ScoreAuthorityForbiddenPatchFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/ScoreAuthorityForbiddenPatchFlow.astro";
import EvalTransitionFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/EvalTransitionFlow.astro";
---

<ChapterShell chapterId="06" locale="en">
  <div slot="thesis">
    <p>
      How can Maka learn from many real runs and turn experience into the next system version —
      without letting the Agent currently executing a user task rewrite itself? Put self-iteration
      outside the interactive Runtime: Runtime produces unconfusable run facts; AHE consumes an
      identity-bound target snapshot and evidence; it proposes a bounded, falsifiable change manifest;
      independent evaluation decides whether to keep it. Key line:
      <strong>Event Log makes experience replayable; the AHE boundary makes change falsifiable.</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <Section
    id="scene"
    label="§06 · Scene"
    title="From “this task failed” to “the next system should differ”"
    lede="One Self-check repairs the current task; systemic failure needs an outer experimental boundary."
  >
    <p>
      Suppose ten long tasks run, and four fail in similar places: the Agent understands the goal, stops
      too early after tool failure, and Self-check treats incomplete results as acceptable. One Run can
      only repair the current task; one Self-check can only point at gaps inside a bounded Turn budget.
      The real question: do these failures mean the system prompt, tool contracts, context policy, or
      Headless policy itself must change?
    </p>
    <p>
      Handing every trace to another model and letting it edit the repo immediately asks: which Maka
      version is being changed? Which files are control surface vs evidence surface? Is “fixed” a
      narrative, or are there failure cases and predictions? Did the candidate only memorize seen
      cases? Was the failure product behavior, eval infra, or missing authority scores? When a change
      is useless or regresses, how do we return to the last stable lineage?
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="keystone"
    label="§06 · Keystone"
    title="Self-iteration is an outer loop, not Runtime recursion"
    lede="The system being improved must not simultaneously be fact recorder, change proposer, and final judge."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      prototype
      caption="Fig. 1 · Runtime plane produces exportable evidence; Evolution plane proposes a bounded manifest; independent evaluation keeps or rolls back."
      alt="Left Runtime plane (tasks→events→projection→read-only export); dashed Evolution plane (AHE Controller, Change Manifest, independent eval); invariant: AHE makes change falsifiable."
    >
      <AheBoundaryKeystone />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Runtime plane</strong> — runs model/tool interaction; records events, permissions,
        artifacts, and task state; serves the current user Turn.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Evolution plane</strong> — aggregates evidence across runs, proposes candidates,
        compares baseline vs candidate; does not serve the current Turn.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      AHE does not join an in-flight user dialogue and does not hold Runtime tool privileges. Maka can
      improve itself without making the improved system also the fact recorder, proposer, and judge.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="experience"
    label="§06 · Experience"
    title="The Event Log becomes an experience base, not only a recovery base"
    lede="AHE must not swallow unbounded JSONL; normalize through TaskRun projection first."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 2 · Read-only export chain: Events → Project → Normalize → Bind target → Export CLI."
      alt="Five-step evidence export pipeline ending at a read-only CLI."
    >
      <EvidenceExportFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Evidence export chain">Runtime / Task Events
        ↓ project
TaskRunProjection
        ↓ normalize and classify
Harness Results + Execution Lineage + Trace Index + Failure Digest
        ↓ bind to
Target Snapshot</pre>
    <p>
      Projection supplies stable task semantics (final status, artifacts, Self-check, workspace
      observation, score authority) — it does not replace raw facts. The index layer helps a controller
      locate failure classes, Self-check divergence, final workspace, source coverage, and lineage gaps;
      the raw-trace layer (only with explicit <code>--include-events</code>) returns to canonical Runtime
      Events to verify whether the projection omitted a causal chain — the third payoff of the log-first
      architecture from earlier chapters: history can be reinterpreted by new projections.
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">History aside</p>
      <p>
        Target protocol / evidence export mechanisms:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/411")}>maka:pr:411</a>,
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/413")}>maka:pr:413</a>. Architecture chapter land:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/776")}>maka:pr:776</a>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="target"
    label="§06 · Target Snapshot"
    title="Declare what may be improved first"
    lede="The most dangerous default is “the whole repo is editable.”"
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 3 · Editable surface vs read-only evidence plane: maka-runtime-evidence must never be a patch target."
      alt="Left: allowed target surface. Right: forbidden maka-runtime-evidence."
    >
      <ReadonlyEvidencePlaneFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      <code>MakaAheTargetSnapshot</code> (exported today as <code>maka.ahe-target.v2</code>) lists an
      explicit component map:
    </p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><code>maka-system-prompt</code> — editable</li>
      <li><code>maka-heavy-task-policy</code> — editable</li>
      <li><code>maka-tool-contracts</code> — editable</li>
      <li><code>maka-context-management</code> — editable</li>
      <li><code>maka-permission-policy</code> — editable</li>
      <li><code>maka-headless-evaluation</code> — editable</li>
      <li><code>maka-runtime-evidence</code> — <strong>read-only</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Each component carries <code>sourceRefs</code>. The sharpest piece is read-only
      <code>maka-runtime-evidence</code>:
      <strong>the ledger that grounds judgment must not also be a candidate patch target</strong> —
      otherwise the easiest “improvement” is rewriting the scoreboard, deleting failures, or making
      evidence friendlier to the candidate.
    </p>
    <p>
      Snapshot identity binds managed source bytes and component topology (content identity), not an
      export timestamp. <code>buildMakaAheTargetSnapshot</code> resolves each source ref to an ordinary
      in-repo file, rejects symlink escape, records SHA-256 digest and byte size per source, hashes the
      manifest itself, and binds <code>snapshotId</code> to that manifest plus normalized topology. Same
      sources and topology → same id; any registered source change → new id. Legacy v1 remains readable
      but is not upgraded or pretended to be content-bound evidence.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="export"
    label="§06 · Evidence Export"
    title="Turn run results into conservative evidence"
    lede="Read-only boundary: read an existing TaskRun store; do not re-execute tasks."
  >
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="AHE export CLI">maka eval ahe export &lt;taskRunId...&gt; \
  --store &lt;out&gt;/runs \
  --repo &lt;maka-repo-root&gt; \
  --out &lt;evidence-dir&gt; \
  [--include-events]</pre>
    <p>Key artifacts a reader should be able to name:</p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><code>target-snapshot.json</code> — which Maka target this evidence belongs to</li>
      <li><code>harness-results.json</code> — normalized status and score authority</li>
      <li><code>trace-index.json</code> — task → messages / events / transcript / tool results / artifacts</li>
      <li><code>traces/&lt;taskRunId&gt;/task-run.json</code> · <code>task-events.jsonl</code> (payload-safe; never mislabeled as Runtime Events)</li>
      <li>
        <code>execution-lineage.json</code> — binds Target, TaskRun, Attempt, AgentRun, and
        Runtime/Task coverage (<code>maka.ahe.execution_lineage.v1</code>; see
        <a href={localePath("en", "chapters/01-log-is-the-runtime") + "#execution-evidence"}
          >§01 · #execution-evidence</a
        >)
      </li>
      <li><code>messages.json</code> · AgentRun <code>inspect.json</code> (payload-safe)</li>
      <li><code>runtime-events.jsonl</code> — canonical Runtime Events, only with <code>--include-events</code></li>
      <li><code>failure-digest.json</code> — deterministic failure summary, Self-check divergence, hygiene, digest-bound debug refs</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Export is deterministic: identical snapshot, projection, source ledgers, run id, and export time
      can regenerate stable JSON. Materialized file refs carry SHA-256 digests and byte sizes. Without
      <code>--include-events</code>, raw Runtime Event payloads are explicitly marked as policy
      omissions — not silently claimed to exist. <code>failure-digest.json</code> is not another model
      summary; deterministic code organizes it from the TaskRun projection.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="authority"
    label="§06 · Authority"
    title="Bucket authority before learning"
    lede="Feedback may propose hypotheses; only allowed authority may change formal success counts."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4 · Authority buckets: official pass/fail · infra/excluded · self_check_only · unscored; Self-check cannot mint official."
      alt="Four columns: official, non-product, feedback self_check_only, unscored."
    >
      <AuthorityBucketFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      Result buckets include
      <code>official_pass</code> / <code>official_fail</code>,
      <code>infra_failed</code>, <code>excluded</code>,
      <code>self_check_only</code>, and <code>unscored</code>. Authority labels include
      <code>official_verifier</code> / <code>official_scorer</code> / <code>self_check</code> /
      <code>analysis_only</code>. The protocol forbids Self-check from declaring official pass/fail —
      the same conclusion as §05 (“Self-check is forever advisory”).
    </p>
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4b · scoreAuthority() export ladder + staged_patch forbidden surface; admission ≠ executor."
      alt="Two columns: scoreAuthority derivation and forbidden patch surface."
    >
      <ScoreAuthorityForbiddenPatchFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <h3 class="subhead">scoreAuthority export ladder (code)</h3>
    <p>
      <code>scoreAuthority()</code> in <code>ahe-evidence-export.ts</code> is a deterministic ladder,
      not a slogan:
    </p>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>
        score.<code>authority</code> is <code>authoritative: true</code> with
        <code>source === 'official_harbor_verifier'</code> → <code>official_scorer</code>
      </li>
      <li>Else the same on verifier → <code>official_verifier</code></li>
      <li>Else Self-check / heavy-task check evidence present → <code>self_check</code></li>
      <li>Else → <code>analysis_only</code></li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Then <code>resultStatus</code>: handle <code>excluded</code> / <code>infra_failed</code> first;
      <code>official_pass</code> / <code>official_fail</code> only when authority is
      <code>official_*</code>. Validator (<code>validateMakaAheRunResult</code>) hard-requires official
      status to carry official authority — a Self-check pass lands in <code>self_check_only</code> (or
      similar non-official buckets). Export also warns when non-authoritative pass evidence appears
      outside official buckets.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="manifest"
    label="§06 · Change Manifest"
    title="A change must become a falsifiable hypothesis first"
    lede="AHE cannot submit only a diff; it must submit a machine-checkable experiment card."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 5 · Manifest → independent evaluation → Accept/Rollback; evolution forms lineage outside the Runtime."
      alt="Five steps: Target snap, Manifest, Independent eval, Accept?, Lineage."
    >
      <ManifestEvaluateFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Falsifiable candidate">Observed failure
    + root-cause hypothesis
    + bounded source change
    + predicted wins
    + predicted risks
    + validation set
    + rollback criteria
    = falsifiable candidate</pre>
    <p>
      <code>MakaAheChangeManifest</code> must declare: which registered components changed; which
      baseline failure evidence supports the change; root cause; targeted fix; which tasks are predicted
      to improve; which tasks may regress; validation dataset; and rollback criteria. Patches today
      allow only <code>applyMode: "staged_patch"</code>.
    </p>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Forbidden patch surface" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Rejected</th>
            <th scope="col">Why</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Absolute / <code>\</code> / <code>..</code></th>
            <td>Must be repo-relative POSIX</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>.git/</code> · <code>node_modules/</code> · <code>dist/</code></th>
            <td><code>FORBIDDEN_PATCH_PATH_*</code> prefixes and path parts</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">path ∉ editable component <code>sourceRefs</code></th>
            <td>Not an admitted editable surface</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>applyMode ≠ staged_patch</code></th>
            <td>Only staged admission is accepted</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>maka-runtime-evidence</code></th>
            <td><code>editable: false</code> — evidence plane cannot be candidate-patched</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      The validator also requires at least one failure case, predicted fix, risk case, validation task,
      and rollback criterion. This remains admission validation, not a patch executor — a valid
      manifest is not auto-applied, and the protocol does not prove the diff itself is safe.
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">History aside · mechanism</p>
      <p>
        Evidence export:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/413")}>maka:pr:413</a>; official result export:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/417")}>maka:pr:417</a>. Contracts:
        <code>ahe-evidence-export.ts</code> · <code>ahe-target-protocol.ts</code> · paired
        <code>__tests__</code>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="evaluation"
    label="§06 · Evaluation"
    title="Do not ask only whether the aggregate score rose"
    lede="The core is per-task transitions, not a single aggregate score."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 6 · Evaluation transitions: fail_to_pass / pass_to_pass / pass_to_fail / fail_to_fail; regressions and missed predictions must stay visible."
      alt="Four transition cells plus footer on predictedFixes and regressions."
    >
      <EvalTransitionFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      <code>MakaAheChangeEvaluation</code> distinguishes
      <code>fail_to_pass</code>, <code>fail_to_fail</code>, <code>pass_to_pass</code>,
      <code>pass_to_fail</code>, <code>new_pass</code> / <code>new_fail</code>, and
      <code>infra_or_excluded</code>, and tracks
      <code>predictedFixesObserved</code> / <code>predictedFixesMissed</code> /
      <code>regressions</code>. A controller can then answer: did predicted wins happen? were risk
      predictions validated? did one target case sacrifice previously passing cases? did the score move
      only because more cells were excluded?
    </p>
    <p>
      Current protocol defines the evaluation data shape, but the same module does not yet ship a full
      change-evaluation validator, automatic keep/discard controller, or AHE runner — the closed loop
      remains Target / an external controller.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="adjacent"
    label="§06 · Adjacent"
    title="Prompt Optimization Loop: adjacent, not wired through"
    lede="A specialized system-prompt optimizer ≠ a completed general AHE closed loop."
  >
    <p>
      <code>prompt-optimization-loop.ts</code> shows a narrower but executable self-iteration: multiple
      baseline runs estimate a noise band; held-in / held-out split; the meta-agent sees only held-in;
      each prompt candidate becomes a Git commit first; held-out is not wasted unless held-in beats
      noise / avoids reward-hack quarantine; acceptance is only keep/discard; discard rolls back the
      candidate commit; a WAL supports replay/resume; cost / infra-failure / round hard caps bound the
      loop.
    </p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><strong>AHE target protocol</strong> — general evolution boundary (components, evidence, manifest, evaluation); currently needs an external controller to close the loop.</li>
      <li><strong>Prompt Optimization Loop</strong> — forced to edit only the system prompt; already has an internal controller and WAL.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      They may later share snapshot identity, evidence taxonomy, candidate lineage, and acceptance
      primitives — but today they must not be taught as one already-connected call chain.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="invariants"
    label="§06 · Invariants"
    title="Three invariants that must hold"
    lede="Immutable evidence + versioned target + falsifiable prediction + independent comparison + reversible lineage."
  >
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>
        <strong>The evidence plane must not be rewritten by the candidate</strong> — candidates may
        change prompts / tool contracts / context policy, but not the Runtime evidence ledger used as
        the comparison basis in the same patch.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Every result must bind a target identity</strong> —
        <code>MakaAheRunResult</code> carries batch <code>runId</code>, <code>snapshotId</code>,
        <code>taskRunId</code>, <code>taskId</code>, and a digest-bearing
        <code>executionLineageRef</code>. Scores without target identity and lineage must not enter
        cross-version comparison.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No counterexample set, no acceptable self-iteration</strong> — manifests must include
        risk cases and rollback criteria; evaluation must keep <code>pass_to_fail</code>. Proving only
        that targeted failures improved, without watching existing capability, is directed overfitting.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Controlled self-iteration">Immutable evidence
  + versioned target
  + bounded editable surface
  + falsifiable prediction
  + independent comparison
  + reversible lineage
  = controlled self-iteration</pre>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="why-not"
    label="§06 · Boundary"
    title="Why AHE is not just a Runtime Tool"
    lede="improve_yourself would mix permissions and time scales that should stay separate."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>The current-task Agent would touch both the user workspace and the Maka source workspace</li>
      <li>The running version would decide how to edit its own evaluation and evidence</li>
      <li>One Turn’s token / timeout / cancel semantics would carry cross-task experiments</li>
      <li>A user-task failure could directly trigger repository mutation</li>
      <li>Restoring a Session would have to restore a code-version lineage</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The outer loop costs protocol and artifacts, but buys clearer authority, isolation, and time
      scale. Only when Maka can prove in-Runtime mutation has equal isolation and recoverability is it
      worth reopening this boundary.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="current"
    label="§06 · Current vs Target"
    title="What Current can do, and what Target still lacks"
    lede="Do not claim Maka already rewrites its own code unsupervised."
  >
    <p><strong>Dependable today:</strong></p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Content-addressed <code>maka.ahe-target.v2</code> (legacy v1 remains readable)</li>
      <li>Source-backed component map distinguishing editable vs evidence-only</li>
      <li>Read-only evidence export; results conservatively bucketed by authority / accounting status</li>
      <li>Versioned run results bound to digest-bearing execution lineage</li>
      <li>Trace index separates Task Events from optional canonical Runtime Events</li>
      <li>Failure digest exposes Self-check divergence / hygiene / final status</li>
      <li>Change-manifest validator bounds components, paths, and minimum experiment declarations</li>
      <li>CLI can export baseline evidence, but does not run AHE or apply patches</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Target closed loop still needs</p>
      <p>
        Stronger Git-commit or content binding; full hash binding between manifest and actual diff;
        general candidate workspace / patch executor / sandbox; change-evaluation validator and explicit
        keep/discard; iteration WAL / resume fingerprint / lineage; dataset partition and leak
        prevention; cost / round / concurrency / regression budgets; writing candidate decisions back to
        an evolution ledger — mature self-iteration should have a smaller change surface, stronger
        evidence binding, and clearer stop conditions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="failure"
    label="§06 · Failure"
    title="The outer loop must also be a durable loop"
    lede="Export failure must not mutate TaskRun; incomplete evaluation must not auto-promote lineage."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Missing/escaping source refs or illegal component maps → snapshot build fails; TaskRun unchanged.</li>
      <li>Self-check only, no formal result → <code>self_check_only</code> / <code>unscored</code>; never fake success.</li>
      <li>Manifest fails validation → reject; no half-applied state.</li>
      <li>Candidate execution interrupted → general AHE runner is not in the protocol module yet; Target wants an append-only iteration WAL.</li>
      <li>Incomplete evaluation → keep infra / excluded / unscored / missing separate; “no regression observed” ≠ “proved no regression.”</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="figure-note">
      Closing line: self-iteration is not self-belief — it is a repeatable process of refutation. Maka
      preserves experience as evidence, then lets a separate evolution loop earn every change.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <div slot="outline">
    <ul class="outline-list">
      <li>Keystone + export file inventory + authority buckets + manifest + eval transitions</li>
      <li>Honest Prompt Optimization Loop adjacency; three invariants</li>
      <li>History asides <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/411")}>maka:pr:411</a> ·
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/413")}>maka:pr:413</a> ·
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/776")}>maka:pr:776</a></li>
      <li>Current read-only protocol vs Target full controller: written (CN+EN ship together)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</ChapterShell>

